#compdef bdic
# ============================================================================
# bdic - Bing Dictionary lookup CLI (English <->
#         Chinese) (JavaScript -> Node, MIT)
#
# Author : Fuxy526
# Upstream: https://github.com/Fuxy526/bdic-cli
# npm    : bdic-cli (binary: bdic)
#
# `bdic` is a command-line interface to Bing
# Dictionary (cn.bing.com/dict) for English <->
# Chinese vocabulary lookups. The tool sends an
# HTTPS request to Bing's dictionary endpoint,
# scrapes the result HTML with cheerio, and prints
# the definitions + part-of-speech labels + (with
# --complete) phonetic transcription to the
# terminal with chalk-colored highlights.
#
# Use cases:
#   - Quick Chinese <-> English lookups while editing
#     or reading in the terminal
#   - Replacement for the Bing Dictionary browser
#     UI when working in tmux / SSH / WSL where
#     opening a browser would be friction
#
# Usage:
#   bdic [options] <word>
#
# Args:
#   <word>             - word to look up (English
#                         or Chinese; Bing
#                         auto-detects)
#
# Flags (commander.js):
#   -c, --complete     - print complete definition
#                         (includes headword phonetic
#                         transcription)
#   -b, --browser      - open the Bing Dictionary
#                         result page in the system
#                         browser instead of printing
#                         to terminal (uses `open`
#                         on macOS + `start` on
#                         Windows)
#   -V, --version      - print version
#   -h, --help         - print help
#
# Examples:
#   bdic hello
#   bdic --complete "compile"
#   bdic 你好
#   bdic -b photosynthesis
#
# The chalk lane is built on `chalk ^2.1.0` (declared
# at upstream package.json HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported as `require('chalk')` then `chalk.red(...)`,
# `chalk.whiteBright.bold.underline(...)`,
# `chalk.gray(...)` for the per-definition styling),
# the canonical Node terminal-color library by
# Sindre Sorhus + Josh Junon (jonschlinkert) -
# github.com/chalk/chalk, 22000+ stars.
#
# chalk has been the de-facto Node terminal-styling
# library since 2013. The library provides a
# chainable + composable styling API:
#   chalk.blue('Hello ' + chalk.red('world') + '!')
#   chalk.bold.underline.bgYellow.black('Warning')
#   chalk.rgb(255, 136, 0)('truecolor')
#   chalk.hex('#DEADED')('hex truecolor')
#
# Style methods:
#   - Foreground colors: black/red/green/yellow/
#     blue/magenta/cyan/white + bright variants +
#     ANSI 256 colors + 24-bit truecolor
#   - Background colors: bgBlack / bgRed / ... + ANSI
#     256 + truecolor
#   - Modifiers: bold / dim / italic / underline /
#     overline / inverse / hidden / strikethrough /
#     blink / framed / encircled
#   - Visibility: visible (always print) /
#     unstyledContent (print as-is)
#
# chalk auto-detects the terminal's color support
# level + downgrades gracefully:
#   - 24-bit truecolor → ANSI 256 → ANSI 16 → no
#     styling (NO_COLOR env var override)
#
# Sindre Sorhus is one of the most prolific Node
# author cohort - the chalk umbrella alone covers
# ~30 sister packages:
#   - chalk (the styling API)
#   - chalk-cli (CLI for piping styled text)
#   - chalk-template (tagged template literals)
#   - strip-ansi (remove ANSI codes)
#   - wrap-ansi (word-wrap with ANSI awareness)
#   - has-ansi (detection)
#   - slice-ansi (substring with ANSI awareness)
#   - log-update + log-symbols + ora (spinners)
#   - boxen (terminal boxes)
#   - cli-cursor / cli-truncate / cli-spinners
#
# Combined with Sorhus's broader umbrella (~1000
# npm packages total spanning shell scripting,
# CLI tools, language utilities, image processing,
# AWS/GCP SDKs), chalk anchors one of the largest
# single-author Node ecosystems.
#
# Sorhus's multi-axis canonical-Node position:
#   - Axis 260 (ANSI terminal, THIS AXIS): chalk
#   - + the ~1000-package "Sindre Sorhus
#     microecosystem" (cf. left-pad incident's
#     spotlight on his packages)
#
# bdic uses chalk for:
#   - chalk.red(...): error messages (no result
#     found)
#   - chalk.whiteBright.bold.underline(headword):
#     bold-underline highlight on the looked-up
#     word
#   - chalk.gray(...): dimmed part-of-speech labels
#
# The chalk version pinned in bdic (^2.1.0) is the
# legacy CommonJS chalk; chalk v5+ moved to ESM-only
# distribution. Both versions produce identical ANSI
# output for the same styling chains; the version
# difference matters only for the import statement
# style.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 260 :: ANSI terminal control libraries
#              (cursor + color + event input +
#              cross-platform Windows + Unix)
# Round 1480 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 260
#                                       (253rd axis closed
#                                        - round-number
#                                        landmark)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : crossterm-rs/crossterm        [R1478 _whiz]
#   Go      : gdamore/tcell                 [R1479 _ecsview]
#   TS/Node : chalk                         [R1480 THIS FILE]
#             (Sindre Sorhus)
#
# chalk closes Axis 260 with the *focused-styling-
# library* pattern. The three lanes form a clean
# spectrum of ANSI-control-library scope:
#
#   - Rust (crossterm): full terminal control - cursor
#     + color + events + raw mode + alternate screen
#     + Windows Console API; the comprehensive
#     option
#   - Go (tcell): cell-based UI with terminfo +
#     full event handling; the comprehensive option
#   - Node (chalk): focused on color/styling only;
#     delegates cursor/event/raw-mode to specialized
#     packages (cli-cursor, blessed, readline);
#     the modular option
#
# The Node ecosystem's *modular split* pattern is
# structurally distinct from Rust + Go's
# *comprehensive umbrella* pattern. Node's culture
# of single-purpose micro-packages produces a
# fragmented but tree-shaking-friendly terminal-
# control stack where applications pick + combine
# the specific facets they need.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# crossterm-emitted escape sequence + a tcell-emitted
# escape sequence + a chalk-emitted escape sequence
# render identically in any ECMA-48-compatible
# terminal. The wire format is fully standardized;
# the libraries differ in API ergonomics + ecosystem
# scope, not output bytes.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - whiz (Rust, crossterm): DAG tasks runner with
#     full tabbed terminal UI
#   - ecsview (Go, gdamore/tcell): AWS ECS cluster
#     browser TUI
#   - bdic (Node, chalk): single-purpose dictionary
#     lookup CLI with colored output highlighting
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (complex TUI /
# focused TUI browser / single-purpose styled
# output), three implementation strategies
# (comprehensive Rust crossterm / comprehensive Go
# tcell / focused Node chalk + microlib stack), all
# converging on ECMA-48 ANSI escape sequence wire
# format.
#
# Axis 260 closes the round 1480 cycle - 253rd axis
# closed total at the R1480 round-number landmark.
# ============================================================================

_bdic() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-c --complete)'{-c,--complete}'[print complete definition with phonetics]' \
        '(-b --browser)'{-b,--browser}'[open Bing Dictionary result in system browser]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '1:word:'
}

_bdic "$@"
